      "by\n```\n\nNow we need to prove this theorem. The theorem states that given a convex set `C` in ℝ³, and functions `x, y: Fin 2 → Fin 3 → ℝ` and `z: Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2) → Fin 3 → ℝ` such that for all `i, j` and set `s`, the point `x i + y j + z s` is in `C` if and only if `(i, j)` is in `s`, we derive a contradiction.\n\nThe key insight is that the functions `x, y, z` would allow us to construct points in `C` that violate the convexity property. Specifically, if we can find a set of points `{p₁, p₂, p₃}` in `C` such that they are not collinear, then this would be a contradiction because a convex set must contain all line segments between its points.\n\nLet's continue with the proof:\n\n```tactics\n  have h1 := hxy 0 0 (∅ : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h1\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 0 + z ∅` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 0)` is in `∅`, which is false. So we get that `x 0 + y 0 + z ∅` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h2 := hxy 0 0 ({(0, 0)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h2\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 0 + z {(0, 0)}` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 0)` is in `{(0, 0)}`, which is true. So we get that `x 0 + y 0 + z {(0, 0)}` is in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h3 := hxy 0 1 (∅ : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h3\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 1 + z ∅` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 1)` is in `∅`, which is false. So we get that `x 0 + y 1 + z ∅` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h4 := hxy 0 1 ({(0, 1)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h4\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 1 + z {(0, 1)}` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 1)` is in `{(0, 1)}`, which is true. So we get that `x 0 + y 1 + z {(0, 1)}` is in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h5 := hxy 1 0 (∅ : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h5\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 0 + z ∅` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 0)` is in `∅`, which is false. So we get that `x 1 + y 0 + z ∅` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h6 := hxy 1 0 ({(1, 0)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h6\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 0 + z {(1, 0)}` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 0)` is in `{(1, 0)}`, which is true. So we get that `x 1 + y 0 + z {(1, 0)}` is in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h7 := hxy 1 1 (∅ : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h7\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 1 + z ∅` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 1)` is in `∅`, which is false. So we get that `x 1 + y 1 + z ∅` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h8 := hxy 1 1 ({(1, 1)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h8\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 1 + z {(1, 1)}` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 1)` is in `{(1, 1)}`, which is true. So we get that `x 1 + y 1 + z {(1, 1)}` is in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h9 := hxy 0 0 ({(0, 0), (0, 1)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h9\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 0 + z {(0, 0), (0, 1)}` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 0)` is in `{(0, 0), (0, 1)}` or `(0, 1)` is in `{(0, 0), (0, 1)}`. Since both are true, we get that `x 0 + y 0 + z {(0, 0), (0, 1)}` is in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h10 := hxy 0 1 ({(0, 0), (1, 0)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h10\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 0 + y 1 + z {(0, 0), (1, 0)}` is in `C` if and only if `(0, 1)` is in `{(0, 0), (1, 0)}` or `(1, 0)` is in `{(0, 0), (1, 0)}`. Since `(0, 1)` is not in the set and `(1, 0)` is in the set, we get that `x 0 + y 1 + z {(0, 0), (1, 0)}` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h11 := hxy 1 0 ({(0, 0), (1, 1)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h11\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 0 + z {(0, 0), (1, 1)}` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 0)` is in `{(0, 0), (1, 1)}` or `(1, 1)` is in `{(0, 0), (1, 1)}`. Since `(1, 0)` is not in the set and `(1, 1)` is in the set, we get that `x 1 + y 0 + z {(0, 0), (1, 1)}` is not in `C`.\n\n```tactics\n  have h12 := hxy 1 1 ({(0, 1), (1, 0)} : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2))\n  simp at h12\n```\n\nThis gives us that `x 1 + y 1 + z {(0, 1), (1, 0)}` is in `C` if and only if `(1, 1)` is in `{(0, 1), (1, 0)}` or `(1, 0)` is in `{(0, 1), (1, 0)}`. Since neither `(1, 1)` nor `(1, 0)` are in the set, w