      "\n```\n\nThe conjecture is that every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has finite VCₙ dimension. The formalization is as follows:\n\n```tactics\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ³ has VC₂ dimension at most 1.\n\nIn fact, this set n-shatters an infinite set. -/\nlemma vc2_lt_two_of_convex_r3 {C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x y : Fin 2 → Fin 3 → ℝ} {z : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2) → Fin 3 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i j s, x i + y j + z s ∈ C ↔ (i, j) ∈ s) : False := sorry\n```\n\nThis is the formalization of the conjecture. The points in ℝ³ are represented as functions from Fin 3 to ℝ. The points x i + y j + z s must be in C if and only if (i, j) ∈ s. This represents a 2D subspace of ℝ³ because the points x i + y j + z s depend on two indices i and j. If such a set C exists, then it would have VC₂ dimension at most 1, which is less than the conjectured bound. The theorem states that this is impossible, leading to a contradiction.\n\nNow, we need to prove the conjecture. Let's think about how to approach this.\n\nTo prove that every convex set in ℝ³ has VC₂ dimension at most 1, we need to show that there's no convex set in ℝ³ that can shatter 2 points with respect to 2D subspaces.\n\nLet's think about how to construct such a proof. If a convex set C in ℝ³ can shatter 2 points with respect to 2D subspaces, then for each subset of the 2 points, there must be a 2D plane cutting through C such that the subset is precisely the intersection.\n\nBut how can we show that this is impossible? Let's think about the geometry of the situation. If we have a convex set C in ℝ³, and we can find two points p₁, p₂ such that for any subset S of {p₁, p₂}, there's a 2D plane π_S such that S = C ∩ π_S.\n\nNow, for a convex set C, if we have two different 2D planes π₁ and π₂ such that C ∩ π₁ = {p₁} and C ∩ π₂ = {p₂}, then we need to show that this is impossible.\n\nLet's think about how to derive a contradiction from such a setup. If C is convex, and we have points p₁, p₂ in C, then the line segment connecting p₁ and p₂ must also be in C. But if we have planes π₁ and π₂ such that C ∩ π₁ = {p₁} and C ∩ π₂ = {p₂}, then the line segment connecting p₁ and p₂ would have to pass through π₁ at p₁ and π₂ at p₂.\n\nBut how can we show that this is impossible? Let's think about the specific geometry. If we have two points p₁, p₂ in C, then any plane that intersects C in exactly these two points would have to be arranged in a specific way. But for a convex set, having two points with exactly these planes would lead to a contradiction.\n\nLet's try to formalize this in Lean. We need to show that given a convex set C in ℝ³, if there exist points x, y, z such that for all i, j and s, x i + y j + z s ∈ C if and only if (i, j) ∈ s, then this leads to a contradiction.\n\nIn Lean, the proof would look something like this:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic\n```\n\nWe need the necessary libraries for working with convex sets and real numbers.\n\nNow, let's define the theorem statement:\n\n```tactics\n/-!\n# VCₙ dimension of convex sets in ℝⁿ⁺¹, ℝⁿ⁺²\n\nIn the literature it is known that every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3,\nand there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension (even more strongly,\nwhich shatters an infinite set).\n\nThis file proves that every convex set in ℝⁿ has finite VCₙ dimension, constructs a convex set in\nℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension (even more strongly, which n-shatters an infinite set),\nand conjectures that every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has finite VCₙ dimension.\n-/\n\n/-! What's known -/\n```\n\nFirst, we establish some known results. The first lemma states that every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3. This is a known result, but since we're working in Lean, we need to formalize it. The second lemma states that there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension. These are standard results in VC theory.\n\n```tactics\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3. -/\nlemma vc_lt_four_of_convex_r2 {C : Set (Fin 2 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x : Fin 4 → Fin 2 → ℝ} {y : Set (Fin 4) → Fin 2 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s) : False := sorry\n```\n\nThe formalization of the first known result. The statement is using a specific representation of points in ℝ² using Fin 2 → ℝ. The points are represented as functions from Fin 2 (which has 2 elements) to ℝ. The lemma states that if a convex set C in ℝ² can shatter 4 points (represented as x i + y s for i in Fin 4 and s in the power set of Fin 4), then it leads to a contradiction. This is a standard way to represent shattering in the context of VC dimension.\n\nNext, we have the known result that there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension:\n\n```tactics\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VC dimension in ℝ³. -/\nlemma exists_convex_r3_vc_eq_infty :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ) (y : Set ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ),\n      ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n```\n\nThis is the formalization of the known result that there exists a convex set in ℝ³ which shatters an infinite set. The representation is similar: points in ℝ³ are represented as functions from Fin 3 to ℝ. The existence of a set of points x i + y s such that x i + y s ∈ C if and only if i ∈ s for all i and s, would mean that C shatters the set {x i | i ∈ ℕ} with respect to the set {y s | s ∈ Set ℕ}. The dimension here is infinite because we're shattering an infinite set.\n\nNow, we move to the new results. The first new result is that there exists a convex set in ℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension:\n\n```tactics\n/-! What's new -/\n```\n\nThe first new result is the existence of a convex set in ℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension. This is a generalization of the known result for ℝ³. The formalization is as follows:\n\n```tactics\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VCₙ dimension in ℝⁿ⁺². -/\nlemma exists_convex_rn_add_two_vc_n_eq_infty (n : ℕ) :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin (n + 2) 